for Greg to put out more trainings so I can have fun taking them.

00:01:59.519 --> 00:02:06.800
I currently work at Biogene in an awesome team led by Bob Ingle and I'm also part of

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:14.520
the executive committee of the R Validation Hub which now has eight members, the chair

00:02:14.520 --> 00:02:19.080
of the R Validation Hub is Andy Nichols from JSK.

00:02:19.080 --> 00:02:27.279
We have members from Merck, Biogene, Gentech, RStudio, Fastar and the R Validation Hub was

00:02:27.279 --> 00:02:33.039
formed in 2018 and is part of the R Consortium working group.

00:02:33.039 --> 00:02:41.240
We have around 100 members from multiple organizations across the pharmaceutical sector, as you can

00:02:41.240 --> 00:02:50.279
see in the work cloud on the right, our members are Johnson & Johnson, FDA, Amgen, L.A. Lilly

00:02:50.279 --> 00:02:54.559
and about 100 total members.

00:02:54.559 --> 00:03:02.919
Now the R Validation Hub is a cross-industry initiative to enable the use of R by the pharmaceutical

00:03:02.919 --> 00:03:11.220
industry in a regulatory set where the output may be used in submissions to regulatory agencies.

00:03:11.220 --> 00:03:17.740
Now to support our mission, we wrote a white paper titled A Risk-Based Approach for Assessing

00:03:17.740 --> 00:03:21.940
R Package Accuracy Within a Validated Infrastructure.

00:03:21.940 --> 00:03:29.419
This paper was written by Andy Nichols from JSK, Paolo Vargo from Janssen and John Sims

00:03:29.419 --> 00:03:37.460
from Pfizer and the aim of this paper is to propose a possible risk-based approach for

00:03:37.460 --> 00:03:43.460
assessing R package accuracy within a validated infrastructure.

00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:50.940
This white paper addresses concerns raised by a statistician, programmers, quality assurance

00:03:50.940 --> 00:03:57.460
teams and others within the pharmaceutical industry about the use of R and selected R

00:03:57.460 --> 00:04:05.539
packages as a primary tool for a statistical analysis for regulatory submission work.

00:04:05.619 --> 00:04:10.940
Now the white paper is based, or rather the definition that we use of validation in the

00:04:10.940 --> 00:04:18.059
white paper is based on the FDA definition of validation, which you can read more about

00:04:18.059 --> 00:04:22.700
in the linked article.

00:04:22.700 --> 00:04:28.500
And there validation can be separated in three main components, accuracy, reproducibility

00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:31.220
and traceability.

00:04:31.940 --> 00:04:35.420
In the white paper, we focus on accuracy.

00:04:35.420 --> 00:04:43.260
We focus on this qualitative assessment of correctness or freedom from error.

00:04:43.260 --> 00:04:50.100
And in the white paper, we propose a risk-based approach to establish accuracy of those

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:52.540
packages that are contributed packages.

00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:58.980
And so we make a decision between core versus contributed R packages.

00:04:58.980 --> 00:05:07.019
And core packages, we say that those packages that are part of the official R distribution

00:05:07.019 --> 00:05:09.540
as formally released by the R Foundation.

00:05:09.540 --> 00:05:16.820
So these software is commonly referred to as base R plus recommended packages.

00:05:16.820 --> 00:05:24.899
Now these packages are considered to be low risk and we make this determination based on

00:05:24.899 --> 00:05:28.579
how the R Foundation develops the R language.

00:05:28.579 --> 00:05:38.380
And you can read more about how the R Foundation describes and how the R Foundation takes their

00:05:38.380 --> 00:05:43.820
approach to developing the R language, their testing approach and how they release versions

00:05:43.820 --> 00:05:46.260
in the link document.

00:05:46.260 --> 00:05:52.660
And we can, by reading this document, you may agree with us that the R-Core team controls

00:05:52.660 --> 00:05:59.019
R like any of the companies that produces the commercial software that you may buy in

00:05:59.019 --> 00:06:00.700
this space.

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:06.820
So the R packages are, the core R packages are very well controlled and so can be considered

00:06:06.820 --> 00:06:08.459
to be low risk.

00:06:08.459 --> 00:06:14.779
Now the complement, we have those packages that are contributed that are made by the

00:06:14.779 --> 00:06:20.420
community, which are about 70,000 packages now on CRAN.

00:06:20.700 --> 00:06:26.980
The risk of these packages really depends on various factors, like how well is the package

00:06:26.980 --> 00:06:27.980
developed?

00:06:27.980 --> 00:06:30.019
Is it well tested?

00:06:30.019 --> 00:06:36.660
The package may have varying software development life cycles that you should be aware of.

00:06:36.660 --> 00:06:46.019
And you also can check for how much exposure has the package had within the user community.

00:06:46.059 --> 00:06:51.420
And in the white paper, we propose, as I mentioned, an approach to assess the accuracy of the

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:57.140
contributed packages as those core are considered to be low risk.

00:06:57.140 --> 00:07:04.019
So once someone in your company wants to use one of these contributed packages, the question

00:07:04.019 --> 00:07:07.940
is, what steps can you take to start to assess the risk of those packages?

00:07:07.940 --> 00:07:14.899
So the white paper can aid you in taking the first steps to start assessing the risk of

00:07:14.899 --> 00:07:17.739
using an R package.

00:07:17.739 --> 00:07:25.779
So once you have decided that you want to use a package, the next step that we propose

00:07:25.779 --> 00:07:32.540
for you to do is to assess the package based on four criteria, purpose, maintenance, good

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:37.820
practice, community usage and testing.

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:43.540
And so when talking about purpose, it is assumed that any package that we're talking about

00:07:43.540 --> 00:07:48.700
is intended to be used within a GXP workflow.

00:07:48.700 --> 00:07:55.779
So package directly manipulating data, creating graphics, or running a statistical model that

00:07:55.779 --> 00:07:59.339
forms part of the submission, we're referring to those.

00:07:59.339 --> 00:08:05.540
So in terms of risk, any package should be weighted equally.

00:08:05.540 --> 00:08:11.899
But we do recognize that modeling statistical packages deserve special attention.

00:08:11.899 --> 00:08:17.739
And we know that there is an innate difficulty to identify errors in those packages in those

00:08:17.739 --> 00:08:22.660
modeling packages versus those say on the manipulated data.

00:08:22.660 --> 00:08:28.459
So for instance, if you would like to test the arranged function of the plier, it is

00:08:28.459 --> 00:08:29.459
easy to do.

00:08:29.459 --> 00:08:31.220
You can or relatively easy to do.

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:36.299
You can use a small data set to test this function and check that the corresponding

00:08:36.299 --> 00:08:39.659
column has been sorted correctly.

00:08:39.659 --> 00:08:46.099
On the other hand, a statistical models are harder to test, and a statistician can roughly

00:08:46.099 --> 00:08:52.619
check that a model is correct, but not correct to the decimal places.

00:08:52.619 --> 00:08:58.659
Now in terms of maintenance, good practice is good to to address the questions on how

00:08:58.659 --> 00:09:05.900
is the documentation of the package is a source code public on GitHub or any other medium.

00:09:05.900 --> 00:09:12.299
And we do we do know that when you when you expose a package to the community, you helps

00:09:12.299 --> 00:09:18.580
reduce the risk as even if the package has no tests, but it's popular, you know that

00:09:18.580 --> 00:09:21.820
it has been widely used by the community.

00:09:21.820 --> 00:09:32.299
And so lastly, testing is a crucial part of the SDLC and another maintenance best practice

00:09:32.299 --> 00:09:33.299
metric.

00:09:34.299 --> 00:09:40.659
In general, the white paper proposes this workflow, which you are encouraged to read

00:09:40.659 --> 00:09:47.219
more in our website, which I'm going to provide a link to at the end of the presentation.

00:09:47.219 --> 00:09:53.059
Now before showing you the the application that we have been working on, I want to point

00:09:53.059 --> 00:09:58.900
out a misconception with talking about open source software like R.

00:09:59.900 --> 00:10:06.140
It's important to note that no statistical software can purchase as pre-validated software

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:08.520
in this regulatory context.

00:10:08.520 --> 00:10:12.940
So what happened is that validation is up to the user to implement.

00:10:12.940 --> 00:10:16.419
So for instance, SAS is not a pre-validated software.

00:10:16.419 --> 00:10:23.739
However, given the dominance of some of the servers in the industry, many companies have

00:10:23.739 --> 00:10:29.900
collected evidence through a long period of time that details the testing and validation

00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:33.739
of functions, procedures, etc.

00:10:33.739 --> 00:10:41.859
And so when you use the software, rather than reinventing the wheel and duplicating testing,

00:10:41.859 --> 00:10:48.059
which has already been performed in the past by others, we make the decision to use that

00:10:48.059 --> 00:10:54.580
software based on its history of extensive previous use as we decide to do with SAS procedures,

00:10:54.580 --> 00:10:55.580
for instance.

00:10:55.580 --> 00:11:03.659
So following this philosophy, you can see our practice as having received validation

00:11:03.659 --> 00:11:09.380
through a variety of sources, validation by the original authors of the package, by users

00:11:09.380 --> 00:11:16.619
of the package in academia, by users in a wide variety of industries like Google, Amazon,

00:11:16.619 --> 00:11:22.859
Microsoft, by companies such as Mango Solutions, and even by the FDA themselves, who have been

00:11:22.859 --> 00:11:26.359
using our internally now for some time.

00:11:26.359 --> 00:11:33.979
So in the same way that we can trust a longstanding SAS package, we can start thinking about our

00:11:33.979 --> 00:11:36.700
packages in the same way.

00:11:36.700 --> 00:11:42.820
So if we want to, if we believe this to be the case, then we need to look at which packages

00:11:42.820 --> 00:11:46.380
we can add to our safe list.

00:11:47.140 --> 00:11:52.900
To do that, we have been working on the RISCmetric R package, which follows the philosophy in

00:11:52.900 --> 00:12:00.419
the white paper and tries to answer questions like, who are the authors?

00:12:00.419 --> 00:12:03.780
How many times has the package been downloaded?

00:12:03.780 --> 00:12:06.700
Does the package, is the package well tested?

00:12:06.700 --> 00:12:09.219
What is the test coverage of the package?

00:12:09.219 --> 00:12:11.940
Is the source code public?

00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:18.780
And so RISCmetric, as I mentioned, is an R package, which measures the risk of using

00:12:18.780 --> 00:12:20.419
R packages.

00:12:20.419 --> 00:12:26.780
And this risk is calculated based on a number of metrics that are meant to evaluate development

00:12:26.780 --> 00:12:34.219
best practices, code documentation, development sustainability, and community engagement.

00:12:34.219 --> 00:12:38.700
Now it's important to know that this risk, the risk portrayed by RISCmetric does not

00:12:38.739 --> 00:12:45.659
represent the risk of damaging the system in which the package is installed or the risk

00:12:45.659 --> 00:12:48.940
that internal statistical functions are correct.

00:12:48.940 --> 00:12:54.900
Although indirectly, the package does check that the statistical functions are correct

00:12:54.900 --> 00:13:01.340
by looking at the testing, the community usage and the bug reports and so on.

00:13:01.340 --> 00:13:07.179
So if you apply the RISCmetric R package to ggplot, you will obtain a low risk.

00:13:07.179 --> 00:13:12.299
So the lowest risk, the risk ranges from zero to one, zero being the lowest risk, one

00:13:12.299 --> 00:13:15.739
being the high risk, the highest risk that you can get.

00:13:15.739 --> 00:13:19.020
With ggplot, you obtain 0.2.

00:13:19.020 --> 00:13:20.380
So that is a low risk.

00:13:20.380 --> 00:13:27.739
And if you use a new package like roles from the tidy models, which is a new package

00:13:27.739 --> 00:13:32.059
created this year, if I'm not mistaken, you will get a high risk.

00:13:32.059 --> 00:13:37.820
And of course, getting a high risk will point you to directions in which you have to look

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:38.780
further in the package.

00:13:38.780 --> 00:13:40.140
Like, do you have to create tests?

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:41.979
Do you have to provide more documentation?

00:13:41.979 --> 00:13:46.299
But in general, this doesn't mean that you can't use the package, but rather that probably

00:13:46.299 --> 00:13:49.739
you have to make more tests.

00:13:49.739 --> 00:13:56.380
And so let's take a look at the functions inside RISCmetric or the main functions.

